46. Amodio DM, Frith CD: Meeting of minds: the medial frontal cortex and social cognition. Nat Rev Neurosci 2006, 7:268-277.

47. King-Casas B, Tomlin D, Anen C, Camerer CF, Quartz SR, Montague PR: Getting to know you: reputation and trust in a two-person economic exchange. Science 2005, 308:78-83.
48. Tomlin D, Kayali MA, King-Casas B, Anen C, Camerer CF,  Quartz SR, Montague PR: Agent-speciÔ¨Åc responses in the
cingulate cortex during economic exchanges. Science 2006, 312:1047-1050. Subjects performed an interactive decision-making task. It was argued that anterior and posterior cingulate regions were active when subjects observed decisions that had an impact on them even though they were made by others. Conversely, a middle cingulate area was active when the subjects made decisions that affected others. As has been described before [46], the activation patterns were seen only when subjects thought that they were interacting with another real person.
